seemed to come looking for him.</i>

244
00:14:01,383 --> 00:14:02,634
That smells great.

245
00:14:02,718 --> 00:14:03,760
I'll open the wine.

246
00:14:03,844 --> 00:14:05,971
Hey,
you're still testifying against me, right?

247
00:14:11,435 --> 00:14:12,269
Okay.

248
00:14:18,483 --> 00:14:19,651
I got you something.

249
00:14:20,444 --> 00:14:21,570
Oh, good, a book.

250
00:14:22,613 --> 00:14:23,864
Why does this keep happening?

251
00:14:23,947 --> 00:14:25,574
- You'll love it.
- Yeah.

252
00:14:25,657 --> 00:14:26,909
It's like it's about you.

253
00:14:27,659 --> 00:14:30,329
It looks long. I'm not that complicated.

254
00:14:31,163 --> 00:14:34,499
2009, Bordeaux,
I should have decanted it for a bit.

255
00:14:34,583 --> 00:14:35,959
Sip it.

256
00:14:37,836 --> 00:14:38,754
Sorry.

257
00:14:39,713 --> 00:14:41,131
So, where is the good doctor?

258
00:14:43,050 --> 00:14:44,843
- Cliff's in Lauderdale.
- Uh-huh.

259
00:14:44,927 --> 00:14:47,221
He's got a meeting tomorrow
with our bankers.

260
00:14:47,304 --> 00:14:49,097
Must be nice to have bankers.

261
00:14:49,681 --> 00:14:51,016
Don't be pedestrian, Andrew.

262
00:14:51,517 --> 00:14:53,685
Tell me again why he isn't divorcing you.

263
00:14:53,769 --> 00:14:54,978
Cliff adores me.

264
00:14:55,062 --> 00:14:57,189
- Even after he caught us together?
- Uh-huh.

265
00:14:57,272 --> 00:14:58,690
- Really?
- Yes.

266
00:14:58,774 --> 00:15:00,484
I'm easy to forgive, Andrew.

267
00:15:05,781 --> 00:15:07,324
You know, I think Sonny would…

268
00:15:08,283 --> 00:15:09,785
- Oh, my--
- …lift my suspension

269
00:15:09,868 --> 00:15:13,080
if you could get Cliff
to drop the charges.

270
00:15:13,163 --> 00:15:15,123
That's why you invited me over tonight.

271
00:15:15,624 --> 00:15:16,667
That's a false statement.

272
00:15:16,750 --> 00:15:19,169
I invited you here every night this week.

273
00:15:20,170 --> 00:15:21,255
It's true. I'm sorry.

274
00:15:22,256 --> 00:15:25,384
I guess I didn't call you back
'cause I just feel like whatever this is

275
00:15:25,467 --> 00:15:27,886
has reached its natural end.

276
00:15:28,846 --> 00:15:31,014
A trial would be embarrassing
for everyone.

277
00:15:32,057 --> 00:15:34,643
Especially your husband,
the alleged victim.

278
00:15:36,770 --> 00:15:38,063
Alleged?

279
00:15:39,356 --> 00:15:42,276
<i>Andrew! Are you serious?</i>

280
00:15:45,445 --> 00:15:47,072
The fuck?

281
00:15:48,866 --> 00:15:51,410
<i>I mean, I wasn't the only witness.</i>

282
00:15:52,286 --> 00:15:54,454
Everyone heard him screaming,

283
00:15:54,538 --> 00:15:57,291
"Stop, stop, stop!"

284
00:16:04,173 --> 00:16:07,384
<i>Well, I mean,
he did call you a whore prior to that.</i>

285
00:16:07,467 --> 00:16:08,927
I was cheating on him!

286
00:16:09,011 --> 00:16:10,304
And he slapped you.

287
00:16:12,389 --> 00:16:13,390
Hard.

288
00:16:14,766 --> 00:16:15,893
Really is a good year.

289
00:16:19,062 --> 00:16:20,480
Well, I suppose I should go.

290
00:16:43,378 --> 00:16:44,922
You really should decant that.

291
00:16:45,964 --> 00:16:46,798
We finished the good stuff.

292
00:16:46,882 --> 00:16:50,052
This is from a box in the garage.

293
00:16:50,135 --> 00:16:53,388
You know, the detective in me
really gets why Cliff wouldn't leave you.

294
00:16:53,472 --> 00:16:57,392
I mean, he's 60.
Not necessarily a head-turner.

295
00:16:57,476 --> 00:16:59,770
You could stop traffic. You're barely 40.

296
00:16:59,853 --> 00:17:02,523
Forty-two and you know it, but thank you.

297
00:17:02,606 --> 00:17:03,899
But why wouldn't you leave him?

298
00:17:03,982 --> 00:17:07,694
He's a piece of shit,
pill-pushing dermatologist.

299
00:17:07,778 --> 00:17:09,488
You'd get plenty in the split.

300
00:17:09,570 --> 00:17:11,281
Does he have something on you?

301
00:17:12,449 --> 00:17:13,951
No more than I do on him.

302
00:17:14,034 --> 00:17:16,954
You should see his internet history.
He's a total perv.

303
00:17:17,037 --> 00:17:18,955
You ever get choked
while pleasuring yourself?

304
00:17:19,039 --> 00:17:20,999
One time. But it was not on purpose.

305
00:17:21,083 --> 00:17:23,877
I was wearing a tie
and then I kind of tripped.

306
00:17:28,048 --> 00:17:30,300
Okay. You win, Andrew.

307
00:17:31,593 --> 00:17:33,053
I'll talk to Cliff again tomorrow.

308
00:17:33,136 --> 00:17:34,137
Thank you.

309
00:17:35,264 --> 00:17:39,476
I really like being a detective and…

310
00:17:40,894 --> 00:17:43,397
you know, I don't like a lot of things so…

311
00:17:44,439 --> 00:17:45,315
Yeah.

312
00:17:46,149 --> 00:17:48,610
I need some ice in my wine. You?

313
00:17:49,152 --> 00:17:50,112
I'm good.

314
00:17:55,200 --> 00:17:57,411
Andrew! God, no!

315
00:17:57,494 --> 00:18:00,372
- Whose is that?
- Oh, fuck. Bonnie!

316
00:18:00,455 --> 00:18:01,707
It's not what you think it is.

317
00:18:01,790 --> 00:18:05,335
Well, it's exactly what you think
it is, but it's-- Good explanation.

318
00:18:06,545 --> 00:18:07,963
Hey, hold on!

319
00:18:08,046 --> 00:18:09,631
- Bonnie!
- Christ! What did you do?

320
00:18:09,715 --> 00:18:12,301
I didn't do anything! You're overreacting!

321
00:18:23,187 --> 00:18:24,813
<i>Before I go any further here,</i>

322
00:18:24,897 --> 00:18:28,734
<i>I gotta tell you a little story
about a young man over in the Bahamas.</i>

323
00:18:29,651 --> 00:18:33,447
<i>Now, I know it's annoying to leave
this story just when it's getting fun,</i>

324
00:18:33,530 --> 00:18:36,116
<i>but I promise it'll make sense eventually.</i>

325
00:18:37,326 --> 00:18:39,203
<i>Just be patient.</i>

326
00:19:00,182 --> 00:19:04,102
<i>It's hard to imagine someone
living a simpler life than Andrew Yancy,</i>

327
00:19:04,186 --> 00:19:06,563
<i>but Neville Stafford sure as hell did.</i>

328
00:19:07,231 --> 00:19:11,568
<i>His days were filled with fishing,
eating those fish, and not much else.</i>

329
00:19:12,986 --> 00:19:15,822
<i>Heck, as long as Neville had
his little shack in paradise,</i>

330
00:19:15,906 --> 00:19:17,282
<i>he was good to go.</i>

331
00:19:18,742 --> 00:19:20,619
<i>It was his happy place too.</i>

332
00:19:25,415 --> 00:19:28,418
<i>And it shouldn't be lost on you that,
just like Yancy,</i>

333
00:19:28,502 --> 00:19:32,589
<i>Neville considered all the nature
around him to be close, personal friends.</i>

334
00:19:32,673 --> 00:19:33,590
Hey, little man.

335
00:19:35,425 --> 00:19:36,844
Mr. Stafford.

336
00:19:38,345 --> 00:19:40,305
Mr. Stafford.

337
00:19:41,056 --> 00:19:42,766
Neville. What do you want?

338
00:19:42,850 --> 00:19:44,017
Can we talk a bit?

339
00:19:45,435 --> 00:19:48,939
<i>Luckily, Neville had
a buddy inside for backup.</i>

340
00:19:50,482 --> 00:19:52,442
<i>Their partnership was
also like a marriage.</i>

341
00:19:53,110 --> 00:19:55,654
No! Bad monkey. Bad.

342
00:19:55,737 --> 00:19:57,948
Jesus, boy.

343
00:19:58,031 --> 00:19:59,700
Where did you get that ugly thing?

344
00:19:59,783 --> 00:20:02,119
Speak kindly or Driggs will fuck you up.

345
00:20:03,829 --> 00:20:06,415
I won him in a game of dominoes
against an old man in Fresh Creek.

346
00:20:06,498 --> 00:20:08,500
He owed me money. So he told me…

347
00:20:08,584 --> 00:20:10,294
<i>"Driggs is one of the trained monkeys</i>

348
00:20:10,377 --> 00:20:12,880
<i>from the very last Johnny Depp
pirate movie they made out here."</i>

349
00:20:13,755 --> 00:20:16,842
<i>He said I could literally teach him
to do anything I wanted.</i>

350
00:20:19,344 --> 00:20:21,513
Driggs, up.

351
00:20:22,681 --> 00:20:26,143
Up. Up, up, up!

352
00:20:28,437 --> 00:20:29,479
That old man was full of shit.

353
00:20:30,647 --> 00:20:32,733
Now, what do you mean,
I have to leave my home?

354
00:20:33,734 --> 00:20:34,985
We sent notices.

355
00:20:36,612 --> 00:20:37,654
I've been fishing.

356
00:20:37,738 --> 00:20:39,615
- For a month?
- I like fishing.

357
00:20:39,698 --> 00:20:41,575
They're putting up a resort here.

358
00:20:41,658 --> 00:20:44,411
An American gentleman
by the name of Christopher.

359
00:20:44,494 --> 00:20:46,246
He's been buying up all the land.

360
00:20:46,330 --> 00:20:48,123
Discussion over. I'm not selling.

361
00:20:48,207 --> 00:20:49,583
But it's not up to you.

362
00:20:49,666 --> 00:20:51,793
Your half-sister, Samara, in Florida,

363
00:20:51,877 --> 00:20:55,297
she's the official trustee,
and she's sold already.

364
00:20:57,090 --> 00:20:58,091
How can she do this?

365
00:20:58,175 --> 00:21:01,887
Easy now.
She got to split the money with you.

366
00:21:02,471 --> 00:21:05,182
The whole resort's going to be top shelf.

367
00:21:05,265 --> 00:21:09,269
Going to have a tiki bar,
freshwater pools over there,

368
00:21:09,353 --> 00:21:12,189
clay tennis courts, a spa.

369
00:21:12,272 --> 00:21:15,943
They're gonna call it Curly Tail Lane.

370
00:21:16,026 --> 00:21:18,737
Green Beach is what my father
always called this place.

371
00:21:18,820 --> 00:21:20,155
Maybe once upon a time.

372
00:21:21,698 --> 00:21:24,743
<i>He was afraid to tell
the government man what he really thought.</i>

373
00:21:24,826 --> 00:21:25,827
Can I get another beer?

374
00:21:26,662 --> 00:21:27,621
<i>He got over it.</i>

375
00:21:27,704 --> 00:21:28,956
Get the fuck off my land.

376
00:21:33,460 --> 00:21:36,713
<i>Neville wasn't the only one
feeling like the world was out to get him.</i>

377
00:21:36,797 --> 00:21:39,424
<i>For the tenth time, Bonnie,
I didn't chop anyone up.</i>

378
00:21:40,008 --> 00:21:41,218
Call me back.

379
00:21:42,928 --> 00:21:45,681
<i>Luckily for Yancy,
he had someone to take it out on.</i>

380
00:21:45,764 --> 00:21:48,183
What do you mean your clients
can't find the house?

381
00:21:49,184 --> 00:21:51,687
I just told you the big yellow one.

382
00:21:52,521 --> 00:21:54,398
Hey, excuse me.

383
00:21:57,651 --> 00:22:01,071
There's a dead raccoon in my house.

384
00:22:01,154 --> 00:22:02,906
<i>This was not news to Yancy.</i>

385
00:22:02,990 --> 00:22:04,449
Not good. How'd it get there?

386
00:22:04,533 --> 00:22:05,534
I don't know.

387
00:22:05,617 --> 00:22:07,911
The damn thing looks like it got pancaked
by a truck or something.

388
00:22:07,995 --> 00:22:09,079
- In your house?
- Yeah.

389
00:22:10,581 --> 00:22:11,623
I'm Evan Shook.

390
00:22:13,000 --> 00:22:14,877
- Big dog.
- Okay.

391
00:22:14,960 --> 00:22:18,172
So look, I called animal control,
but I got people coming over any minute.

392
00:22:18,255 --> 00:22:20,215
They flew in from Dallas.
I could really use a hand, bro.

393
00:22:20,299 --> 00:22:21,675
Okay, here's the thing--
Evan Shook, is it?

394
00:22:21,758 --> 00:22:23,594
- Uh-huh.
- I wanna help you, I do.

395
00:22:23,677 --> 00:22:27,347
But it is really bad luck to disturb
a dead animal, and I can't afford that.

396
00:22:27,431 --> 00:22:29,099
Bad luck? What are you talking,
voodoo or some shit?

397
00:22:29,183 --> 00:22:31,268
No, it's like an instant curse.
You can borrow my shovel.

398
00:22:31,351 --> 00:22:33,645
No! Dude, it reeks to high hell.

399
00:22:33,729 --> 00:22:36,565
I'm sure it does. I mean,
dead things usually smell pretty bad.

400
00:22:39,151 --> 00:22:40,152
Shit.

401
00:22:40,235 --> 00:22:42,112
- Hey, peace, bro.
- Yeah.

402
00:22:42,196 --> 00:22:45,991
<i>Yancy felt that warm glow he
always got when he made an enemy for life.</i>

403
00:22:46,074 --> 00:22:47,576
Christina, how are you?

404
00:22:47,659 --> 00:22:49,369
What the hell's going on over there?

405
00:22:49,453 --> 00:22:50,996
Dead-raccoon situation.

406
00:22:51,079 --> 00:22:52,915
Cool. You got any food?

407
00:22:54,208 --> 00:22:56,210
The reason I came, Sonny sent me.

408
00:22:57,503 --> 00:22:58,879
What'd you ever do with that arm?

409
00:23:00,422 --> 00:23:03,300
Well, you told me to toss it
in the canal, so I tossed it.

410
00:23:10,557 --> 00:23:12,351
- I still got it.
- That's what I figured.

411
00:23:12,434 --> 00:23:15,020
Wow, you truly never listen to me.

412
00:23:15,687 --> 00:23:18,774
Good news, though, because a woman
came in to report her husband missing

413
00:23:18,857 --> 00:23:20,859
- from a boating accident.
- Well, that took long enough.

414
00:23:20,943 --> 00:23:21,944
She was in Europe.

415
00:23:22,027 --> 00:23:25,155
Old man was heading to the Bahamas
on a fishing trip.

416
00:23:25,239 --> 00:23:28,867
Here's the kicker,
she wants the fucking arm, man.

417
00:23:28,951 --> 00:23:30,035
- S--
- Wow.

418
00:23:30,118 --> 00:23:32,663
She wants to do a church service,
the whole show.

419
00:23:33,163 --> 00:23:36,166
- She needs the arm back to bury it.
- Yeah, that's gonna be a tiny casket.

420
00:23:36,250 --> 00:23:37,918
They'll probably
have a regular-size casket.

421
00:23:38,001 --> 00:23:39,378
That's a big waste of wood.

422
00:23:40,671 --> 00:23:44,091
You know, I should be getting major
brownie points for this from Sonny.

423
00:23:44,883 --> 00:23:48,554
Could you imagine how ugly the press
would be if you lost a dead guy's arm?

424
00:23:48,637 --> 00:23:50,013
Jesus, man.

425
00:23:52,182 --> 00:23:54,142
All right, Sonny's gonna tell the widow

426
00:23:54,226 --> 00:24:00,607
that you're the authorized custodian
of the unclaimed remains or some shit.

427
00:24:00,691 --> 00:24:03,318
Her name's Eve, as in Christmas.

428
00:24:03,402 --> 00:24:05,404
Stripling as in stripper.

429
00:24:05,988 --> 00:24:08,866
- I'm listening.
- All right, here's her number.

430
00:24:09,408 --> 00:24:12,369
Meet her, give her the arm,
then get the hell out of Dodge.

431
00:24:12,452 --> 00:24:15,622
- No talking, no questions.
- Why do you feel like you gotta warn me?

432
00:24:15,706 --> 00:24:17,249
You really wanna have this conversation?

433
00:24:17,332 --> 00:24:20,586
Yeah, I was hoping to. That's why I said
what I said. Sometimes it's fun to talk.

434
00:24:21,170 --> 00:24:23,630
Just behave, man.
She just lost her husband.

435
00:24:27,551 --> 00:24:29,428
<i>I'm sorry for your loss, Mrs. Stripling.</i>

436
00:24:29,511 --> 00:24:33,682
<i>Thank you.
Yeah, it's awful. It's just awful.</i>

437
00:24:34,892 --> 00:24:36,685
<i>So, where do you want to meet up?</i>

438
00:24:36,768 --> 00:24:39,479
<i>There's a shopping center
about halfway between us.</i>

439
00:24:39,563 --> 00:24:42,274
<i>It'll be easy to find me.
I'll be wearing a blue hat.</i>

440
00:24:54,119 --> 00:24:55,204
Hi.

441
00:24:55,287 --> 00:24:56,330
Hey.

442
00:24:56,413 --> 00:24:59,750
- Are you Detective Yancy?
- And you must be Mrs. Stripling.

443
00:24:59,833 --> 00:25:01,251
Eve's fine.

444
00:25:01,335 --> 00:25:02,377
- Hi.
- Hi.

445
00:25:04,796 --> 00:25:06,840
This kind of feels like a drug deal.

446
00:25:10,052 --> 00:25:13,639
I guess I should take a look, right?

447
00:25:18,560 --> 00:25:21,855
Well, that's how they found it.
You know, just random rigor mortis.

448
00:25:21,939 --> 00:25:23,899
It's-- It is weird, I know.

449
00:25:23,982 --> 00:25:26,193
It's u-- very unique, but it's--

450
00:25:26,276 --> 00:25:29,613
I don't know, but it's uncomfortable.

451
00:25:29,696 --> 00:25:32,950
- It's really uncomfortable.
- Yeah.

452
00:25:36,286 --> 00:25:39,456
It's his ring. It's definitely him.
This sucks.

453
00:25:40,541 --> 00:25:41,542
Fuck!

454
00:25:42,125 --> 00:25:43,627
You doing all right?

455
00:25:43,710 --> 00:25:47,005
I just feel like this isn't even real.
I'm like in a Winn-Dixie, like…

456
00:25:48,841 --> 00:25:50,843
looking at my husband's arm, I just--

457
00:25:53,971 --> 00:25:55,931
- I'm gonna take it.
- No, no, I got this.

458
00:25:58,058 --> 00:26:01,603
- Thanks.
- So, they ever find Nick's boat?

459
00:26:02,271 --> 00:26:05,315
No. They just found
some cushions and spare gas cans.

460
00:26:05,399 --> 00:26:09,570
There was a fuel slick, like five miles
off the coast of Sombrero Lighthouse.

461
00:26:10,362 --> 00:26:11,822
Anybody else on board?

462
00:26:11,905 --> 00:26:13,574
Just my Nicky.

463
00:26:13,657 --> 00:26:16,952
He was on his way up
to Cay Sal to meet up with some friends.

464
00:26:17,995 --> 00:26:21,206
<i>Yancy knew with all of his heart
that the smart move was to say goodbye</i>

465
00:26:21,290 --> 00:26:25,919
<i>to Eve Stripling and the arm that smelled
like onions and never look back.</i>

466
00:26:26,003 --> 00:26:27,379
Let's sit in the car.

467
00:26:27,462 --> 00:26:29,798
- I-- No, I'm so sorry. I--
- Just a few questions, all routine.

468
00:26:29,882 --> 00:26:31,550
I actually have to go.

469
00:26:34,928 --> 00:26:36,346
When did you learn Nick was missing?

470
00:26:36,930 --> 00:26:38,473
I was in Paris.

471
00:26:38,557 --> 00:26:41,018
Yeah, it was a birthday present from Nick.

472
00:26:41,602 --> 00:26:42,603
